    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "During the SARS-CoV-2 pandemic, patients with COVID-19 pneumonia tend to deteriorate and develop acute respiratory distress syndrome, [1] . Most of these patients receive mechanical ventilation (MV) and many may benefit from prone positioning (PP) as a life-saving maneuver in the setting of severe hypoxemia, aiming to attempt to open the collapsed and congested parenchymal lung segments [2] . These patients require detailed cardiocirculatory evaluation due to the effects of sedation, and the high respiratory pressures which affect venous return and right ventricular performance [3] . This evaluation often includes echocardiography.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 134,
                    "end": 137,
                    "text": "[1]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 390,
                    "end": 393,
                    "text": "[2]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 585,
                    "end": 588,
                    "text": "[3]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "To the editors"
        },
        {
            "text": "It is known that mechanically ventilated-patients generally do not present good ultrasound (US) windows to allow high-quality echocardiography due to the \"curtain effect\" of the left lung that reduces the ability of the US beam to penetrate to the heart and return to the transducer.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "To the editors"
        },
        {
            "text": "Furthermore, echocardiography may be required during PP. The \"gold-standard\" solution to these issues is transesophageal echocardiography (TEE). While TEE performed in the PP has been reported as a safe procedure, [4] , in our opinion, one limitation may be the position of the neck and head of the patient that is laterally rotated and may make it difficult to introduce the TEE probe. Additionally, given the high number of patients requiring this type of evaluation and the number of devices available, TEE is often a logistic challenge.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 214,
                    "end": 217,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "To the editors"
        },
        {
            "text": "In order to overcome these technical issues trans-thoracic echocardiography (TTE) may play an important role as it is non-invasive, reproducible and easily available. Unlike the technique for TTE in the prone patient reported by Ugalde et al. [5] , we performed TTE in prone-positioned patients during MV without the need to adopt the \"swimming position\" (extension of left arm above head) and without the need to elevate the left shoulder with pillows. We temporarily deflated the lower thoracic section of the air mattress in order to position the probe as best to obtain the apical-fourchambers (A-4-C) view, taking advantage of the gravitational effect on the heart causing it to slide closer to the chest wall. The operator is positioned to the left of the patient and uses their left 3 hand to position the transducer. The only US window that we could assess was the A-4-C ( Figure   1 ). It allows the evaluation of many of the parameters included in the assessment of left and right ventricular (LV, RV) performance: LV ejection-fraction, mitral annular plane excursion, the diastolic function parameters (mitral valve and annular Doppler velocities), the aortic valve Doppler flow velocity (tilting the probe we can obtain the apical-5-chambers view), the RV end-diastolic diameter and its ratio with the LV end-diastolic diameter, the RV systolic performance by tricuspid annular plane excursion (TAPSE), and pulmonary artery systolic pressure from the tricuspid regurgitation peak Doppler velocity.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 243,
                    "end": 246,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 881,
                    "end": 891,
                    "text": "Figure   1",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF1"
                }
            ],
            "section": "To the editors"
        },
        {
            "text": "We used this approach in 8 patients to assess cardiac performance. In only one case was the quality of the US view poor, and this was in a patient with a markedly increased BMI of 60 kg/m 2 .",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "To the editors"
        },
        {
            "text": "In our experience during the current SARS-CoV-2 outbreak, prone-position TTE is feasible and provides sufficient information to monitor some basic aspects of cardiac performance. ",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "To the editors"
        }
    ],
